China Stocks: Huaneng Power, Inner Mongolia Baotou, PetroChina

-- B y   B l o o m b e r g   N e w s
-- 
2011-05-06T08:10:29Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-05-05/shanghai-electric-shenzhen-agri-zijin-china-equity-preview.html
Shares of the following companies had
unusual moves in  China  trading. Stock symbols are in parentheses
as of 3 p.m. close.  The Shanghai Composite Index, which tracks the bigger of
China’s stock exchanges, fell 24.96 points, or 0.9 percent, to
2,847.44. The  CSI 300 Index (SHSZ300)  declined 0.9 percent to 3,098.26.  Commodity producers: PetroChina Co. (601857 CH), the
nation’s biggest oil company, slid 2.2 percent to 11.15 yuan.
Zijin Mining Group Co. (601899 CH), China’s largest gold
producer, lost 0.7 percent to 7.18 yuan. Aluminum Corp. of China
Ltd. (601600 CH), the listed unit of nation’s biggest maker of
the lightweight metal and also called Chalco, fell 1.6 percent
to 10.19 yuan.  Commodities dropped the most in more than two years on
concern that economic growth will slow as central banks seek to
cool inflation by raising borrowing costs. The Standard & Poor’s
GSCI Index of 24 raw materials fell 6.5 percent yesterday, the
most since Jan. 7, 2009. Copper slid 3.3 percent in  New York 
yesterday, gold dropped 2.2 percent and oil slumped 8.6 percent.  Power producers:  Huaneng Power International Inc. (902)  (600011
CH), a unit of China’s largest power group, gained 2.9 percent
to 6.47 yuan, the highest since Nov. 11. Shanghai Electric Power
Co. (600021 CH), supplier of a third of the electricity in
China’s richest city, advanced 3.1 percent to 6.01 yuan.  The director of China’s electricity regulator said the
nation is able to make short-term increases in on-grid power
prices as part of efforts to reduce supply shortages, Xinhua
News Agency reported, citing Tan Rongyao, director of the State
Electricity Regulatory Commission. Such a price increase would
spur the “enthusiasm” of coal-fired power generators, Xinhua
reported yesterday, citing Tan.  Inner Mongolia Baotou Steel Rare-Earth Hi-Tech Co. (600111
CH), the nation’s biggest producer of the metal, jumped 7.9
percent to 89.44 yuan, the most in a month. The government plans
to consolidate the rare-earth industry in the company’s home
province, National Business Daily reported today. The
consolidation will include all 35 rare earth producers and
Baotou Steel Rare-Earth will take over four producers, according
to the report.  Shanghai Pharmaceuticals Holding Co. (601607 CH), China’s
second-largest drug distributor, added 1.8 percent to 20.27 yuan
after being suspended over the past four days. The company said
in a today’s statement it aims to raise as much as HK$15.3
billion ($1.97 billion) in a sale of 664.2 million shares in a
public offering in  Hong Kong .  Shenzhen Agricultural Products Co. (000061 CH), a
wholesaler and supermarket chain operator, retreated 2.7 percent
to 18.20 yuan after saying it plans to raise as much as 2.5
billion yuan ($385 million) in a private placement by selling up
to 151 million shares.  --Zhang Shidong. Editor: Allen Wan  To contact Bloomberg News staff for this story:
